1
00:00:04,480 --> 00:00:06,000
Out of my way!

2
00:00:07,840 --> 00:00:08,840
(POUNDING ON DOOR)

3
00:00:09,120 --> 00:00:10,480
Doctor!

4
00:00:11,240 --> 00:00:12,440
Doctor!

5
00:00:13,920 --> 00:00:15,240
Doctor!

6
00:00:16,720 --> 00:00:18,080
Doctor!

7
00:00:20,520 --> 00:00:22,240
Where's the Doctor?

8
00:00:23,840 --> 00:00:25,000
Doctor who?

9
00:00:25,160 --> 00:00:26,280
(DOCTOR SNEEZING)

10
00:00:40,240 --> 00:00:41,280
(GROWLING)

11
00:00:41,360 --> 00:00:44,240
You know, this isn't nearly
as bad as it looks.

12
00:00:46,640 --> 00:00:47,960
"At the personal intervention
of the King,

13
00:00:48,040 --> 00:00:49,680
"the unnamed Doctor was incarcerated

14
00:00:49,760 --> 00:00:51,320
"without trial in the Tower of London."

15
00:00:51,400 --> 00:00:52,920
Okay, but it doesn't have to be him.

16
00:00:53,000 --> 00:00:55,880
"According to contemporary accounts,
two nights later, a magical sphere,

17
00:00:55,960 --> 00:00:58,840
"some 20 feet across,
was seen floating away from the Tower,

18
00:00:58,920 --> 00:01:02,480
-"bearing the mysterious Doctor aloft."
-Okay, it's him.

19
00:01:02,720 --> 00:01:03,720
AMY: There's more.

20
00:01:03,800 --> 00:01:06,000
Doctor. Doctor, what can you see?

21
00:01:06,320 --> 00:01:08,880
Is the commandant's office
painted a sort of green colour

22
00:01:08,960 --> 00:01:10,000
with a big flag on the wall?

23
00:01:10,360 --> 00:01:11,400
(ALARM SOUNDING)

24
00:01:11,480 --> 00:01:13,120
-I think the answer is probably "yes".
-(DOGS BARKING)

25
00:01:13,240 --> 00:01:14,640
-Get him up!
-Ow!

26
00:01:15,800 --> 00:01:17,720
It's like he's being
deliberately ridiculous,

27
00:01:17,800 --> 00:01:18,920
trying to attract our attention.

28
00:01:19,000 --> 00:01:20,080
Are you watching this again?

29
00:01:20,160 --> 00:01:22,920
-(DOORBELL RINGS)
-Yeah, I've explained the jokes.

30
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:25,080
So what are you saying?
Do you really think he's back there

31
00:01:25,160 --> 00:01:27,160
trying to wave to us
out of history books?

32
00:01:27,240 --> 00:01:29,720
Hey, it's the sort of thing he'd do.
Thanks.

33
00:01:29,800 --> 00:01:31,040
Yeah, but why?

34
00:01:31,120 --> 00:01:32,600
Well, he said he'd be in touch.

35
00:01:33,040 --> 00:01:34,880
-Two months ago.
-Two months is nothing.

36
00:01:34,960 --> 00:01:36,840
He's up to something.
I know he is. I know him.

37
00:01:39,480 --> 00:01:40,480
What is it?

38
00:01:40,800 --> 00:01:41,800
Amy?

39
00:01:41,880 --> 00:01:44,040
A date, a time, a map reference.

40
00:01:44,120 --> 00:01:45,600
I think it's an invitation.

41
00:01:45,680 --> 00:01:47,360
-From who?
-It's not signed.

42
00:01:47,960 --> 00:01:49,640
Look, Tardis blue.

43
00:02:11,480 --> 00:02:13,080
(ALARM SOUNDING)

44
00:02:13,800 --> 00:02:15,200
You'd better get down here, sir.

45
00:02:15,520 --> 00:02:17,320
She's doing it again.

46
00:02:17,760 --> 00:02:19,400
Dr Song, sir.

47
00:02:19,520 --> 00:02:21,040
She's packing.

48
00:02:22,000 --> 00:02:24,560
Says she's going to
some planet called America.

49
00:02:35,720 --> 00:02:37,600
-Thanks!
-DRIVER: You're very welcome!

50
00:02:38,680 --> 00:02:40,320
This is it, yeah? The right place?

51
00:02:40,560 --> 00:02:43,080
Uh, nowhere, middle of?

52
00:02:43,160 --> 00:02:44,560
Yeah, this it.

53
00:02:45,280 --> 00:02:46,440
Howdy.

54
00:02:47,040 --> 00:02:48,160
-Doctor!
-(LAUGHS)

55
00:02:48,240 --> 00:02:49,920
It's the Pond!

56
00:02:50,320 --> 00:02:53,000
-Hey!
-Come on, Pond. Hello, Pond! Come here!

57
00:02:53,120 --> 00:02:55,240
So someone's been a busy boy, then, eh?

58
00:02:55,320 --> 00:02:56,680
-Did you see me?
-Of course.

59
00:02:56,760 --> 00:02:57,800
-Stalker.
-Flirt.

60
00:02:57,920 --> 00:03:00,800
-Husband.
-Rory the Roman! Oh, come here!

61
00:03:01,320 --> 00:03:02,960
Ooh, ah.

62
00:03:03,440 --> 00:03:04,520
Hey, nice hat.

63
00:03:04,600 --> 00:03:06,680
I wear a Stetson now. Stetsons are cool.

64
00:03:06,800 --> 00:03:07,800
(GUN FIRES)

65
00:03:12,360 --> 00:03:14,080
Hello, sweetie.

66
00:03:15,120 --> 00:03:17,000
Right, then, where are we?

67
00:03:17,080 --> 00:03:19,360
-Have we done Easter Island yet?
-Um...

68
00:03:19,440 --> 00:03:20,920
Yes! I've got Easter Island.

69
00:03:21,080 --> 00:03:22,840
They worshipped you there.

70
00:03:23,200 --> 00:03:24,640
Have you seen the statues?

71
00:03:24,920 --> 00:03:25,920
Jim the Fish.

72
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:27,440
Oh! Jim the Fish.

73
00:03:27,520 --> 00:03:29,000
How is he?

74
00:03:29,320 --> 00:03:30,880
Still building his dam.

75
00:03:31,760 --> 00:03:33,440
Sorry, what are you two doing?

76
00:03:33,520 --> 00:03:35,840
They're both time travellers,
so they never meet in the right order.

77
00:03:35,920 --> 00:03:37,400
They're syncing their diaries.

78
00:03:37,480 --> 00:03:38,960
So what's happening, then?

79
00:03:39,520 --> 00:03:41,280
Because you've been up to something.

80
00:03:43,040 --> 00:03:44,120
I've been running,

81
00:03:44,840 --> 00:03:46,120
faster than I've ever run,

82
00:03:46,920 --> 00:03:49,040
and I've been running my whole life.

83
00:03:49,800 --> 00:03:51,400
Now it's time for me to stop.

84
00:03:52,840 --> 00:03:55,280
And tonight, I'm going to
need you all with me.

85
00:03:56,800 --> 00:03:57,920
Okay.

86
00:03:58,280 --> 00:03:59,560
We're here. What's up?

87
00:03:59,840 --> 00:04:00,920
A picnic.

88
00:04:01,000 --> 00:04:02,120
And then a trip.

89
00:04:02,680 --> 00:04:05,400
Somewhere different,
somewhere brand new.

90
00:04:06,000 --> 00:04:07,160
Where?

91
00:04:08,160 --> 00:04:09,400
Space.

92
00:04:10,720 --> 00:04:12,160
1969.

93
00:04:12,880 --> 00:04:15,440
(DOCTOR WHO THEME)

94
00:04:51,480 --> 00:04:52,480
DOCTOR: Salud!

95
00:04:52,560 --> 00:04:53,800
ALL: Salud!

96
00:04:53,880 --> 00:04:56,520
So when are we going to 19697

97
00:04:57,120 --> 00:04:58,760
And since when do you drink wine?

98
00:04:58,840 --> 00:05:00,680
I'm 1103. I must've drunk it sometime.

99
00:05:02,920 --> 00:05:04,560
Oh, why, it's horrid!

100
00:05:05,800 --> 00:05:07,000
I thought it would taste
more like the gums.

101
00:05:07,080 --> 00:05:10,040
11037 You were 908
the last time we saw you.

102
00:05:10,120 --> 00:05:12,920
And you've put on a couple of pounds.
I wasn't going to mention it.

103
00:05:20,760 --> 00:05:21,880
Who's that?

104
00:05:21,960 --> 00:05:23,240
Hmm? Who's who?

105
00:05:24,760 --> 00:05:26,000
Sorry, what?

106
00:05:26,120 --> 00:05:28,280
What did you see?
You said you saw something.

107
00:05:28,400 --> 00:05:29,400
No, I didn't.

108
00:05:29,480 --> 00:05:30,720
Ah! The moon.

109
00:05:31,200 --> 00:05:32,280
Look at it.

110
00:05:32,360 --> 00:05:34,160
Of course, you lot did a lot
more than look, didn't you?

111
00:05:34,240 --> 00:05:36,480
A big silvery thing in the sky.

112
00:05:36,560 --> 00:05:37,920
You couldn't resist it.

113
00:05:38,000 --> 00:05:39,360
Quite right.

114
00:05:39,440 --> 00:05:40,800
The moon landing was in '69.

115
00:05:41,720 --> 00:05:42,720
Is that where we're going?

116
00:05:42,800 --> 00:05:45,560
Oh, well, a lot more happens in '69
than anyone remembers.

117
00:05:46,720 --> 00:05:48,240
Human beings.

118
00:05:49,160 --> 00:05:50,880
I thought I'd never get done saving you.

119
00:06:09,440 --> 00:06:10,440
Who's he?

120
00:06:11,400 --> 00:06:12,400
Oh, my God!

121
00:06:16,960 --> 00:06:18,560
DOCTOR: You all need to stay back.

122
00:06:20,040 --> 00:06:22,480
Whatever happens now,
you do not interfere.

123
00:06:24,520 --> 00:06:25,640
Clear?

124
00:06:32,040 --> 00:06:33,800
RORY: That's an astronaut.

125
00:06:34,120 --> 00:06:35,960
That's an Apollo astronaut in the lake.

126
00:06:36,040 --> 00:06:37,160
Look.

127
00:06:43,760 --> 00:06:45,040
Hello.

128
00:06:46,080 --> 00:06:47,600
It's okay. I know it's you.

129
00:06:53,200 --> 00:06:54,560
Well, then.

130
00:07:05,440 --> 00:07:07,040
What's he doing?

131
00:07:07,440 --> 00:07:09,400
-(GUN FIRES)
-Doctor!

132
00:07:09,520 --> 00:07:10,920
Amy, stay back!

133
00:07:11,120 --> 00:07:12,760
-(GUN FIRES)
-The Doctor said stay back!

134
00:07:13,360 --> 00:07:15,360
-We have to stay back!
-No! No!

135
00:07:20,280 --> 00:07:21,480
AMY: Doctor!

136
00:07:28,560 --> 00:07:30,040
I'm sorry.

137
00:07:42,920 --> 00:07:43,920
(GUN FIRES)

138
00:07:45,360 --> 00:07:48,480
RIVER: No! Doctor!
AMY: Doctor, please!

139
00:07:53,680 --> 00:07:55,400
AMY: River. River!

140
00:07:55,480 --> 00:07:57,000
(DEVICE BEEPS)

141
00:08:00,240 --> 00:08:02,840
No. No.

142
00:08:03,680 --> 00:08:05,600
(RIVER FIRING GUN)

143
00:08:09,600 --> 00:08:10,600
(CLICKS)

144
00:08:15,680 --> 00:08:17,160
Of course not.

145
00:08:21,520 --> 00:08:23,160
AMY: River, he can't be dead.

146
00:08:23,560 --> 00:08:25,320
This isn't possible.

147
00:08:26,480 --> 00:08:29,920
Whatever that was, it killed him
in the middle of his regeneration cycle.

148
00:08:30,480 --> 00:08:31,880
His body was already dead.

149
00:08:33,160 --> 00:08:35,280
He didn't make it to the next one.

150
00:08:35,760 --> 00:08:39,400
AMY: But maybe he's a clone
or a duplicate or something.

151
00:08:39,480 --> 00:08:41,400
I believe I can save you some time.

152
00:08:44,560 --> 00:08:46,400
That most certainly is the Doctor.

153
00:08:48,120 --> 00:08:50,360
And he is most certainly dead.

154
00:08:50,920 --> 00:08:52,680
He said you'd need this.

155
00:08:58,840 --> 00:09:00,200
Gasoline?

156
00:09:04,760 --> 00:09:06,600
A Time Lord's body is a miracle,

157
00:09:07,400 --> 00:09:08,760
even a dead one.

158
00:09:09,600 --> 00:09:10,760
There are whole empires out there

159
00:09:10,840 --> 00:09:12,840
who'd rip this world apart
for just one cell.

160
00:09:14,640 --> 00:09:16,200
We can't leave him here.

161
00:09:16,920 --> 00:09:18,320
Or anywhere.

162
00:09:18,600 --> 00:09:19,600
Wake up.

163
00:09:19,680 --> 00:09:22,400
Go on, wake up!
You stupid, bloody idiot.

164
00:09:26,440 --> 00:09:28,200
What do we do, Rory?

165
00:09:29,840 --> 00:09:31,160
We're his friends.

166
00:09:33,360 --> 00:09:35,280
We do what the Doctor's
friends always do.

167
00:09:38,120 --> 00:09:39,400
As we're told.

168
00:09:41,360 --> 00:09:42,920
There's a boat.

169
00:09:45,960 --> 00:09:47,160
If we're going to do this,

170
00:09:49,120 --> 00:09:50,040
let's do it properly.

171
00:10:28,480 --> 00:10:29,920
Who are you?

172
00:10:31,120 --> 00:10:32,800
Why did you come?

173
00:10:33,120 --> 00:10:34,880
The same reason as you.

174
00:10:45,800 --> 00:10:47,040
Dr Song,

175
00:10:48,680 --> 00:10:49,760
Amy,

176
00:10:50,560 --> 00:10:51,720
Rory.

177
00:10:52,240 --> 00:10:55,040
I'm Canton Everett Delaware III.

178
00:10:56,880 --> 00:10:58,800
I won't be seeing you again,

179
00:10:59,560 --> 00:11:02,160
but you'll be seeing me.

180
00:11:14,080 --> 00:11:15,200
Four.

181
00:11:16,600 --> 00:11:17,600
Sorry, what?

182
00:11:17,680 --> 00:11:20,000
The Doctor numbered the envelopes.

183
00:11:20,080 --> 00:11:22,800
You got 3, I was 2, Mr Delaware was 4.

184
00:11:22,880 --> 00:11:24,000
So?

185
00:11:24,080 --> 00:11:25,640
So where's 1?

186
00:11:26,240 --> 00:11:28,000
What, you think he invited someone else?

187
00:11:28,080 --> 00:11:29,240
Well, he must have.

188
00:11:29,320 --> 00:11:31,360
RIVER: He planned all of this,
to the last detail.

189
00:11:31,440 --> 00:11:32,920
Will you two shut up? It doesn't matter.

190
00:11:33,000 --> 00:11:34,360
-RIVER: He was up to something.
-He's dead.

191
00:11:34,440 --> 00:11:36,760
"Space 1969." What did he mean?

192
00:11:37,000 --> 00:11:38,840
You're still talking,
but it doesn't matter.

193
00:11:38,920 --> 00:11:42,080
-Hey, it mattered to him.
-So it matters to us.

194
00:11:42,160 --> 00:11:45,160
-He's dead.
-But he still needs us.

195
00:11:46,160 --> 00:11:47,560
I know.

196
00:11:47,960 --> 00:11:50,160
Amy, I know.

197
00:11:50,520 --> 00:11:52,560
But right now, we have to focus.

198
00:11:56,120 --> 00:11:57,240
Look.

199
00:11:59,680 --> 00:12:01,440
Excuse me, who was sitting over there?

200
00:12:01,520 --> 00:12:02,800
Some guy.

201
00:12:02,880 --> 00:12:04,760
The Doctor knew
he was going to his death,

202
00:12:04,840 --> 00:12:06,240
so he sent out messages.

203
00:12:06,480 --> 00:12:08,840
When you know it's the end,
who do you call?

204
00:12:09,200 --> 00:12:10,480
Uh, your friends, people you trust.

205
00:12:10,560 --> 00:12:11,840
Number 1.

206
00:12:12,600 --> 00:12:14,360
Who did the Doctor trust the most?

207
00:12:20,920 --> 00:12:22,360
This is cold.

208
00:12:23,160 --> 00:12:25,240
Even by your standards, this is cold.

209
00:12:25,320 --> 00:12:27,080
Or "hello", as people used to say.

210
00:12:27,280 --> 00:12:28,320
Doctor?

211
00:12:28,480 --> 00:12:30,520
I just popped out
to get my special straw.

212
00:12:31,080 --> 00:12:32,720
It adds more fizz.

213
00:12:37,560 --> 00:12:40,640
You're okay. How can you be okay?

214
00:12:40,720 --> 00:12:42,160
Hey, of course I'm okay.

215
00:12:42,240 --> 00:12:44,720
I'm always okay. I'm the king of okay.

216
00:12:45,440 --> 00:12:47,240
Oh, that's a rubbish title.
Forget that title.

217
00:12:47,320 --> 00:12:51,160
Rory the Roman!
That's a good title. Hello, Rory.

218
00:12:52,520 --> 00:12:54,400
And Dr River Song.

219
00:12:54,800 --> 00:12:56,520
Oh, you bad, bad girl.

220
00:12:56,600 --> 00:12:58,400
What trouble have you got
for me this time?

221
00:12:59,880 --> 00:13:01,000
Okay.

222
00:13:02,760 --> 00:13:04,760
I'm assuming that's for
something I haven't done yet.

223
00:13:05,880 --> 00:13:07,000
Yes, it is.

224
00:13:07,080 --> 00:13:08,240
Good. Looking forward to that.

225
00:13:08,320 --> 00:13:09,720
I don't understand.

226
00:13:11,280 --> 00:13:12,520
How can you be here?

227
00:13:13,280 --> 00:13:14,760
I was invited.

228
00:13:15,480 --> 00:13:17,600
Date, map reference.

229
00:13:17,680 --> 00:13:20,000
Same as you lot, I assume. Otherwise,
it's a hell of a coincidence.

230
00:13:20,080 --> 00:13:21,080
River, what's going on?

231
00:13:21,160 --> 00:13:22,680
Amy, ask him what age he is.

232
00:13:22,760 --> 00:13:24,080
-That's a bit personal.
-Tell her.

233
00:13:24,160 --> 00:13:26,240
-Tell her what age you are.
-909.

234
00:13:26,800 --> 00:13:29,000
-Yeah, but you said you were...
-So where does that leave us, huh?

235
00:13:29,600 --> 00:13:30,680
Jim the Fish?

236
00:13:30,800 --> 00:13:32,200
Have we done Jim the Fish yet?

237
00:13:32,320 --> 00:13:34,040
Who's Jim the Fish?

238
00:13:34,840 --> 00:13:36,240
I don't understand.

239
00:13:36,360 --> 00:13:37,480
Yeah, you do.

240
00:13:37,560 --> 00:13:39,760
I don't! What are we all doing here?

241
00:13:44,520 --> 00:13:46,080
We've been recruited.

242
00:13:46,680 --> 00:13:50,600
Something to do with space, 1969,

243
00:13:50,960 --> 00:13:55,680
and a man called
Canton Everett Delaware III.

244
00:13:56,720 --> 00:13:58,160
Recruited by who?

245
00:13:59,640 --> 00:14:03,000
Someone who trusts you
more than anybody else in the universe.

246
00:14:04,480 --> 00:14:06,000
And who's that?

247
00:14:06,960 --> 00:14:08,240
Spoilers.

248
00:14:10,920 --> 00:14:12,400
1969, that's an easy one!

249
00:14:12,560 --> 00:14:14,240
Funny how some years are easy.

250
00:14:14,320 --> 00:14:16,200
Now, 1482, full of glitches.

251
00:14:16,280 --> 00:14:19,640
Now, then, Canton Everett Delaware III.
That was his name, yeah?

252
00:14:19,720 --> 00:14:22,640
How many of those can there be?
Well, three, I suppose.

253
00:14:27,600 --> 00:14:30,560
Rory, is everybody cross with me
for some reason?

254
00:14:31,400 --> 00:14:33,000
I'LL find out.

255
00:14:42,160 --> 00:14:43,240
Explain it again?

256
00:14:43,320 --> 00:14:45,680
The Doctor we saw on the beach
is a future version,

257
00:14:46,040 --> 00:14:47,960
200 years older than the one up there.

258
00:14:48,040 --> 00:14:50,280
But all that's still going to happen,
he's still going to die?

259
00:14:50,600 --> 00:14:52,000
We're all going to do that, Amy.

260
00:14:52,080 --> 00:14:55,400
We're not all going to arrange
our own wake and invite ourselves.

261
00:14:56,920 --> 00:15:00,640
So, the Doctor, in the future,
knowing he's going to die,

262
00:15:00,720 --> 00:15:05,840
recruits his younger self
and all of us to...to what, exactly?

263
00:15:06,520 --> 00:15:07,560
Avenge him?

264
00:15:07,640 --> 00:15:10,240
-Mmm-mmm. Avenging's not his style.
-Save him.

265
00:15:10,320 --> 00:15:12,000
RORY: Yeah, that's not really
his style, either.

266
00:15:12,120 --> 00:15:13,280
Well, we have to tell him.

267
00:15:13,360 --> 00:15:14,840
We've told him all we can.

268
00:15:15,080 --> 00:15:17,160
We can't even tell him
we've seen his future self.

269
00:15:19,880 --> 00:15:21,720
He's interacted with his own past.

270
00:15:22,080 --> 00:15:23,400
It could rip a hole in the universe.

271
00:15:23,480 --> 00:15:24,840
Except he's done it before.

272
00:15:24,920 --> 00:15:27,240
And, in fairness,
the universe did blow up.

273
00:15:27,320 --> 00:15:31,000
-But he'd want to know!
-Would he? Would anyone?

274
00:15:31,080 --> 00:15:32,880
I'm being extremely clever up here

275
00:15:32,960 --> 00:15:34,880
and there's no one to stand around
looking impressed!

276
00:15:34,960 --> 00:15:36,760
What's the point in having you all?

277
00:15:37,600 --> 00:15:39,360
Couldn't you just slap him sometimes?

278
00:15:39,440 --> 00:15:41,400
River, we can't just let him die.

279
00:15:41,880 --> 00:15:43,280
We have to stop it.

280
00:15:43,480 --> 00:15:45,080
How can you be okay with this?

281
00:15:45,160 --> 00:15:48,560
The Doctor's death doesn't frighten me,
nor does my own.

282
00:15:49,400 --> 00:15:51,440
There's a far worse day coming for me.

283
00:15:55,080 --> 00:15:56,640
Time isn't a straight line.

284
00:15:56,720 --> 00:15:59,440
It's all bumpy-wumpy.
There's loads of boring stuff,

285
00:15:59,520 --> 00:16:02,320
like Sundays and Tuesdays
and Thursday afternoons.

286
00:16:02,600 --> 00:16:04,360
But now and then, there are Saturdays,

287
00:16:04,440 --> 00:16:06,600
big, temporal tipping points
when anything's possible.

288
00:16:06,680 --> 00:16:09,000
The Tardis can't resist them,
like a moth to a flame.

289
00:16:09,080 --> 00:16:11,680
She loves a party,
so I gave her 1969 and NASA,

290
00:16:11,760 --> 00:16:15,120
because that's space in the '60s,
and Canton Everett Delaware III,

291
00:16:15,200 --> 00:16:18,000
and this is where she's pointing.

292
00:16:18,080 --> 00:16:21,920
Washington, DC. April the 8th, 1969.

293
00:16:22,000 --> 00:16:23,240
So why haven't we landed?

294
00:16:23,320 --> 00:16:25,200
-Because that's not where we're going.
-Oh.

295
00:16:25,320 --> 00:16:26,920
-Where are we going?
-Home! Well, you two are.

296
00:16:27,000 --> 00:16:29,520
Off you pop and make babies.
And you, Dr Song, back to prison.

297
00:16:29,600 --> 00:16:32,480
And me?
I'm late for a biplane lesson in 1911.

298
00:16:32,560 --> 00:16:35,480
Or it could be knitting.
Knitting or biplanes, one or the other.

299
00:16:43,160 --> 00:16:44,280
What?

300
00:16:45,080 --> 00:16:47,640
A mysterious summons.
You think I'm just going to go?

301
00:16:49,360 --> 00:16:50,960
Who sent those messages?

302
00:16:53,960 --> 00:16:56,000
I know you know,
I can see it in your faces.

303
00:16:56,080 --> 00:16:57,120
Don't play games with me.

304
00:16:57,200 --> 00:16:58,720
Don't ever, ever think
you're capable of that.

305
00:16:58,800 --> 00:17:00,280
You're going to have to trust us
this time.

306
00:17:00,360 --> 00:17:02,080
DOCTOR: Trust you? Sure.

307
00:17:02,960 --> 00:17:05,440
But first of all, Dr Song,
just one thing.

308
00:17:07,080 --> 00:17:08,480
Who are you?

309
00:17:10,400 --> 00:17:12,720
You're someone from my future,
getting that, but who?

310
00:17:19,000 --> 00:17:20,120
Okay.

311
00:17:20,800 --> 00:17:22,640
Why are you in prison?
Who did you kill?

312
00:17:23,480 --> 00:17:24,600
Hmm?

313
00:17:25,120 --> 00:17:26,640
Now, I love a bad girl, me,

314
00:17:27,920 --> 00:17:29,440
but trust you?

315
00:17:31,160 --> 00:17:32,480
Seriously?

316
00:17:33,880 --> 00:17:35,280
Trust me.

317
00:17:37,840 --> 00:17:38,960
Okay.

318
00:17:43,200 --> 00:17:46,240
You have to do this
and you can't ask why.

319
00:17:46,880 --> 00:17:49,000
Are you being threatened?
Is someone making you say that?

320
00:17:49,080 --> 00:17:50,080
No.

321
00:17:51,160 --> 00:17:52,800
-You're lying.
-I'm not lying.

322
00:17:55,720 --> 00:17:58,440
Swear to me.
Swear to me, on something that matters.

323
00:18:06,520 --> 00:18:07,960
Fish fingers and custard.

324
00:18:17,600 --> 00:18:18,840
My life in your hands,

325
00:18:20,720 --> 00:18:22,120
Amelia Pond.

326
00:18:29,640 --> 00:18:31,040
Thank you.

327
00:18:31,360 --> 00:18:34,560
So! Canton Everett Delaware III.

328
00:18:34,880 --> 00:18:35,880
Who's he?

329
00:18:35,960 --> 00:18:38,080
-Who wants to know?
-Your boss.

330
00:18:38,160 --> 00:18:39,400
I don't have a boss any more.

331
00:18:39,480 --> 00:18:42,720
Maybe you want to tell that
to the President of the United States.

332
00:18:44,280 --> 00:18:46,240
-Ex-FBI. Got kicked out.
-Why?

333
00:18:46,720 --> 00:18:49,040
PRESIDENT: (ON PHONE) I understand
you have a problem with authority.

334
00:18:49,120 --> 00:18:51,840
-Thank you.
-That's not a compliment, son.

335
00:18:51,920 --> 00:18:54,320
Six weeks after he left the Bureau,

336
00:18:54,400 --> 00:18:56,800
the President contacted him
for a private meeting.

337
00:18:56,880 --> 00:18:58,680
Yeah, 1969. Who's President?

338
00:18:58,920 --> 00:19:00,800
This is a personal matter.

339
00:19:01,280 --> 00:19:03,200
I need someone on the outside,

340
00:19:03,360 --> 00:19:04,960
someone with FBI training,

341
00:19:05,120 --> 00:19:06,680
but who's not in contact with them.

342
00:19:06,760 --> 00:19:08,040
I'm flattered.

343
00:19:08,240 --> 00:19:10,680
You were my second choice
for this, Mr Delaware.

344
00:19:10,760 --> 00:19:12,200
That's okay.

345
00:19:12,360 --> 00:19:14,880
You were my second choice
for President, Mr Nixon.

346
00:19:22,680 --> 00:19:24,360
RIVER: Richard Milhous Nixon.

347
00:19:24,440 --> 00:19:25,920
Vietnam, Watergate.

348
00:19:26,000 --> 00:19:28,280
-There's some good stuff, too.
-Not enough.

349
00:19:28,600 --> 00:19:30,280
-Hippie!
-Archaeologist.

350
00:19:31,320 --> 00:19:33,440
Every day, wherever I am,

351
00:19:34,760 --> 00:19:36,040
I get a phone call.

352
00:19:36,120 --> 00:19:37,760
People can't just call you,
Mr President.

353
00:19:39,200 --> 00:19:40,920
It's a direct call every time.

354
00:19:41,440 --> 00:19:43,080
Every day for the last two weeks,

355
00:19:44,080 --> 00:19:45,280
usually late at night.

356
00:19:45,360 --> 00:19:46,800
Man or woman?

357
00:19:47,600 --> 00:19:48,640
Neither.

358
00:19:52,600 --> 00:19:53,840
Listen.

359
00:19:53,920 --> 00:19:55,880
Okay, since I don't know
what I'm getting into this time,

360
00:19:55,960 --> 00:19:58,560
for once, I'm being discreet,
putting the engines on silent.

361
00:20:02,840 --> 00:20:03,880
Did you do something?

362
00:20:03,960 --> 00:20:06,000
No, just watching.

363
00:20:07,080 --> 00:20:09,360
Putting the outer shell on "invisible".
Haven't done this in a while.

364
00:20:09,440 --> 00:20:10,960
Big drain on the power.

365
00:20:11,040 --> 00:20:13,720
-You can turn the Tardis invisible?
-Ha!

366
00:20:14,960 --> 00:20:16,440
Very nearly.

367
00:20:16,840 --> 00:20:18,720
Uh, did you touch something?

368
00:20:18,800 --> 00:20:20,720
Just admiring your skills, sweetie.

369
00:20:20,800 --> 00:20:23,200
Good. You might learn something.

370
00:20:23,280 --> 00:20:24,400
Okay.

371
00:20:27,040 --> 00:20:30,400
Now, I can't check the scanner, it
doesn't work when we're cloaked. Um...

372
00:20:31,360 --> 00:20:33,000
Just give us a mo...

373
00:20:33,080 --> 00:20:34,240
Whoa! Whoa, whoa, whoa.

374
00:20:34,320 --> 00:20:35,800
You lot, wait a moment.

375
00:20:36,720 --> 00:20:38,320
We're in the middle
of the most powerful city

376
00:20:38,400 --> 00:20:40,840
in the most powerful country on Earth.

377
00:20:43,960 --> 00:20:45,680
Let's take it slow.

378
00:20:48,680 --> 00:20:50,600
(PHONE RINGING ON TAPE)

379
00:20:53,840 --> 00:20:55,360
NIXON: Hello?

380
00:20:56,200 --> 00:20:57,640
Who is this?

381
00:20:57,960 --> 00:21:00,200
This is President Nixon. Who's calling?

382
00:21:01,080 --> 00:21:02,800
Is this you again?

383
00:21:02,920 --> 00:21:04,920
-CHILD: Mr President?
-A child.

384
00:21:05,560 --> 00:21:07,480
This is the President, yes.

385
00:21:07,560 --> 00:21:09,200
I'm scared, Mr President.

386
00:21:10,040 --> 00:21:11,680
I'm scared of the spaceman.

387
00:21:11,760 --> 00:21:13,400
-A little girl?
-Boy.

388
00:21:13,480 --> 00:21:15,080
How can you be sure?

389
00:21:15,640 --> 00:21:17,160
NIXON: What spaceman?

390
00:21:18,240 --> 00:21:19,720
Where are you phoning from?

391
00:21:19,800 --> 00:21:21,280
Where are you right now?

392
00:21:22,560 --> 00:21:23,920
Who are you?

393
00:21:24,000 --> 00:21:26,800
CHILD: Jefferson Adams Hamilton.

394
00:21:27,400 --> 00:21:29,080
NIXON: Jefferson, listen to me.

395
00:21:29,840 --> 00:21:31,560
(HANGS UP, DIALLING TONE DRONES)

396
00:21:31,640 --> 00:21:35,000
Surely this is something
the Bureau could handle, sir.

397
00:21:35,080 --> 00:21:36,760
These calls happen wherever I am.

398
00:21:37,760 --> 00:21:39,720
How do I know the Bureau isn't involved?

399
00:21:40,080 --> 00:21:41,920
I can't trust anyone...

400
00:21:53,560 --> 00:21:54,600
Oh!

401
00:21:54,880 --> 00:21:56,040
Hello.

402
00:21:56,560 --> 00:21:58,000
Bad moment.

403
00:21:58,760 --> 00:22:01,600
Oh, look, this is the Oval Office.

404
00:22:01,680 --> 00:22:05,600
I was looking for the, er, Oblong Room.

405
00:22:05,680 --> 00:22:08,000
I'll just be off, then,

406
00:22:08,520 --> 00:22:09,560
shall I?

407
00:22:13,560 --> 00:22:14,960
Every time.

408
00:22:15,040 --> 00:22:16,120
Don't worry!

409
00:22:16,200 --> 00:22:17,480
It always does that when its cloaked.

410
00:22:17,840 --> 00:22:19,120
No! Stop that.

411
00:22:19,200 --> 00:22:21,080
-He said the scanner wouldn't work.
-I know.

412
00:22:22,000 --> 00:22:23,240
Bless.

413
00:22:23,320 --> 00:22:26,160
-Ow, ow...
-Lockdown! Lockdown!

414
00:22:26,880 --> 00:22:28,400
Stop that! Ow!

415
00:22:28,480 --> 00:22:30,760
River, have you got
my scanner working yet?

416
00:22:30,840 --> 00:22:32,040
Oh, I hate him.

417
00:22:32,320 --> 00:22:34,360
-No, you don't!
-AGENT: Get the President out of here!

418
00:22:34,440 --> 00:22:36,240
Sir, you have to go with them now!

419
00:22:36,320 --> 00:22:38,480
River, make her blue again!

420
00:22:49,200 --> 00:22:51,040
What the hell is that?

421
00:22:54,040 --> 00:22:56,840
Mr President, that child just told you

422
00:22:56,920 --> 00:22:58,400
everything you need to know,
but you weren't listening.

423
00:22:58,480 --> 00:23:00,280
Never mind, though,
because the answer's yes.

424
00:23:00,480 --> 00:23:01,840
I'll take the case.

425
00:23:01,920 --> 00:23:03,200
Fellas, the guns, really?

426
00:23:03,280 --> 00:23:06,200
I just walked into the highest security
office in the United States,

427
00:23:06,280 --> 00:23:08,560
parked a big, blue box on the rug.

428
00:23:09,200 --> 00:23:10,800
Do you think you can just shoot me?

429
00:23:10,880 --> 00:23:11,960
They're Americans!

430
00:23:12,040 --> 00:23:13,120
Don't shoot. Definitely no shooting.

431
00:23:13,200 --> 00:23:16,920
RORY: No need to shoot us, either.
Very much not in need of getting shot.

432
00:23:17,000 --> 00:23:18,320
Look, we've got our hands up.

433
00:23:18,400 --> 00:23:21,600
-Who the hell are you?
-Sir, you need to stay back.

434
00:23:21,800 --> 00:23:24,520
But who are they and what is that box?

435
00:23:25,440 --> 00:23:27,320
It's a police box. Can't you read?

436
00:23:27,880 --> 00:23:30,560
I'm your new undercover agent,
on loan from Scotland Yard.

437
00:23:30,640 --> 00:23:32,080
Codename: The Doctor.

438
00:23:32,160 --> 00:23:34,840
These are my top operatives:
The Legs, The Nose

439
00:23:34,920 --> 00:23:36,560
and Mrs Robinson.

440
00:23:36,640 --> 00:23:37,880
-I hate you.
-No, you don't.

441
00:23:37,960 --> 00:23:40,040
-AGENT: Who are you?
-Nah, a boring question.

442
00:23:40,120 --> 00:23:41,960
"Who's phoning you?" That's interesting.

443
00:23:42,040 --> 00:23:44,360
Because Canton III is right,
that was definitely a girl's voice,

444
00:23:44,440 --> 00:23:46,760
which means there's only one place
in America she can be phoning from.

445
00:23:46,840 --> 00:23:47,880
Where?

446
00:23:47,960 --> 00:23:49,600
Do not engage with the intruder,
Mr Delaware.

447
00:23:50,600 --> 00:23:52,040
You heard everything I heard.
It's simple enough.

448
00:23:52,120 --> 00:23:53,680
Give me five minutes, I'll explain.

449
00:23:53,760 --> 00:23:55,720
On the other hand, lay a finger on me

450
00:23:56,080 --> 00:23:59,280
or my friends
and you'll never, ever know.

451
00:23:59,960 --> 00:24:01,120
How did you get it in here?

452
00:24:01,200 --> 00:24:02,800
I mean, you didn't carry it in.

453
00:24:02,880 --> 00:24:04,440
-Clever, eh?
-Love it.

454
00:24:04,560 --> 00:24:06,360
Do not compliment the intruder!

455
00:24:06,440 --> 00:24:07,840
-Five minutes?
-Five.

456
00:24:07,920 --> 00:24:10,560
Mr President, that man is
a clear and present danger to...

457
00:24:10,640 --> 00:24:13,800
Mr President, that man walked in here

458
00:24:13,880 --> 00:24:15,640
with a big, blue box
and three of his friends

459
00:24:16,160 --> 00:24:17,360
and that's the man he walked past.

460
00:24:17,440 --> 00:24:19,200
One of them's worth listening to.

461
00:24:19,720 --> 00:24:22,120
I say we give him five minutes,
see if he delivers.

462
00:24:22,520 --> 00:24:23,560
Thanks, Canton.

463
00:24:23,640 --> 00:24:25,400
If he doesn't, I'll shoot him myself.

464
00:24:25,520 --> 00:24:26,560
Not so thanks.

465
00:24:26,640 --> 00:24:28,760
-Sir, I cannot recommend...
-Shut up, Mr Peterson!

466
00:24:33,040 --> 00:24:34,360
All right.

467
00:24:35,680 --> 00:24:37,120
Five minutes.

468
00:24:44,120 --> 00:24:45,760
I'm going to need a SWAT team,
ready to mobilise,

469
00:24:45,840 --> 00:24:47,720
street-level maps
covering all of Florida,

470
00:24:47,800 --> 00:24:50,080
a pot of coffee,
12 Jammie Dodgers and a fez.

471
00:24:51,480 --> 00:24:52,880
Get him his maps.

472
00:24:58,360 --> 00:24:59,920
-Why Florida?
-That's where NASA is.

473
00:25:00,000 --> 00:25:02,520
She mentioned a spaceman.
NASA's where the spacemen live.

474
00:25:03,080 --> 00:25:06,000
Also, there's another lead
I'm following.

475
00:25:07,240 --> 00:25:09,520
A spaceman,
like the one we saw at the lake.

476
00:25:09,760 --> 00:25:10,920
Maybe.

477
00:25:11,720 --> 00:25:13,000
Probably.

478
00:25:15,200 --> 00:25:17,280
(ALIEN CHITTERING)

479
00:25:23,000 --> 00:25:24,400
Who's that?

480
00:25:28,440 --> 00:25:29,480
I remember.

481
00:25:29,560 --> 00:25:30,560
Amy?

482
00:25:30,840 --> 00:25:32,160
What do you remember?

483
00:25:33,280 --> 00:25:34,840
I don't know. I just...

484
00:25:36,520 --> 00:25:37,720
Amy, what's wrong?

485
00:25:38,200 --> 00:25:39,280
Amy?

486
00:25:39,680 --> 00:25:42,000
-You all right?
-Yeah, no, I'm fine.

487
00:25:42,080 --> 00:25:43,920
I'm just feeling a little sick.

488
00:25:46,320 --> 00:25:47,880
Excuse me,
is there a toilet or something?

489
00:25:47,960 --> 00:25:49,920
Sorry, ma"am,
while this procedure's ongoing,

490
00:25:50,000 --> 00:25:51,480
you must remain within the Oval Office.

491
00:25:51,560 --> 00:25:54,280
Shut up and take her to the restroom.

492
00:25:55,920 --> 00:25:58,440
-This way, ma'am.
-Thanks.

493
00:26:01,560 --> 00:26:03,240
Your five minutes are up.

494
00:26:03,600 --> 00:26:05,240
Yeah? And where's my fez?

495
00:26:12,040 --> 00:26:14,160
Actually, I can usually
manage this alone.

496
00:26:23,480 --> 00:26:25,520
(ALIEN CHITTERING)

497
00:26:31,120 --> 00:26:32,800
I saw you before, at the lake.

498
00:26:33,400 --> 00:26:34,680
And here.

499
00:26:38,120 --> 00:26:39,880
But then I forgot.

500
00:26:40,080 --> 00:26:41,720
How did I forget?

501
00:26:46,080 --> 00:26:47,680
What are you?

502
00:26:48,960 --> 00:26:49,960
(TOILET FLUSHING)

503
00:26:50,200 --> 00:26:52,120
Get back! Stay back from it.

504
00:26:52,960 --> 00:26:54,160
(SCREAMS)

505
00:26:55,280 --> 00:26:58,080
Oh, my God!
What is that? Is that a mask?

506
00:26:58,960 --> 00:27:00,200
Is that a Star Trekthing?

507
00:27:01,000 --> 00:27:02,320
Ben, is that you?

508
00:27:02,400 --> 00:27:03,960
Get back from it, now!

509
00:27:06,120 --> 00:27:07,360
Back from what, honey?

510
00:27:08,960 --> 00:27:10,120
That.

511
00:27:11,800 --> 00:27:12,840
(SCREAMS)

512
00:27:12,920 --> 00:27:15,120
Oh, my God! Look at that.

513
00:27:15,280 --> 00:27:16,600
Is that a Star Trek mask?

514
00:27:17,480 --> 00:27:19,040
Ben, that's got to be you.

515
00:27:20,720 --> 00:27:22,440
Hang on, did I just say all that?

516
00:27:24,160 --> 00:27:26,160
No, please, you've got to stay back.

517
00:27:28,840 --> 00:27:31,000
Back, honey? Back from what?

518
00:27:34,000 --> 00:27:36,400
Oh, those lights. They never fix them.

519
00:27:36,680 --> 00:27:37,720
Look behind you.

520
00:27:37,800 --> 00:27:39,360
Honey, there is nothing...

521
00:27:40,240 --> 00:27:41,440
(SCREAMING)

522
00:27:58,560 --> 00:27:59,560
(AMY PANTING)

523
00:28:01,440 --> 00:28:04,520
You didn't have to kill her.
She couldn't even remember you.

524
00:28:04,600 --> 00:28:05,840
How does that work?

525
00:28:05,920 --> 00:28:08,840
We can only remember you
while we're seeing you, is that it?

526
00:28:12,200 --> 00:28:13,600
Why did you have to kill her?

527
00:28:14,480 --> 00:28:15,760
Joy.

528
00:28:18,600 --> 00:28:21,280
Her name was joy.

529
00:28:22,400 --> 00:28:24,840
Your name is Amelia.

530
00:28:27,280 --> 00:28:30,120
You will tell the Doctor.

531
00:28:30,960 --> 00:28:32,040
Tell him what?

532
00:28:32,120 --> 00:28:34,320
What he must know.

533
00:28:34,840 --> 00:28:38,400
And what he must never know.

534
00:28:38,480 --> 00:28:40,000
How do you know about that?

535
00:28:40,200 --> 00:28:42,320
Tell him.

536
00:28:48,600 --> 00:28:49,880
Are you okay?

537
00:28:51,120 --> 00:28:52,520
I'm fine.

538
00:28:52,600 --> 00:28:53,920
Much better, thanks.

539
00:28:54,600 --> 00:28:56,080
What's that?

540
00:28:58,040 --> 00:28:59,480
It's my phone.

541
00:28:59,560 --> 00:29:00,920
Your phone?

542
00:29:01,480 --> 00:29:02,960
I have to tell the Doctor.

543
00:29:04,040 --> 00:29:05,840
Tell him what, ma'am?

544
00:29:08,200 --> 00:29:10,120
Sorry, I don't know why I said that.

545
00:29:12,120 --> 00:29:13,720
This way, ma'am.

546
00:29:17,920 --> 00:29:18,960
(PHONE RINGING)

547
00:29:20,640 --> 00:29:21,840
The kid?

548
00:29:21,920 --> 00:29:23,560
-Should I answer it?
-Here!

549
00:29:23,640 --> 00:29:26,600
The only place in the United States
that call could be coming from.

550
00:29:26,960 --> 00:29:28,280
See? Obvious, when you think about it.

551
00:29:28,360 --> 00:29:29,400
(PHONE RINGING)

552
00:29:29,480 --> 00:29:31,920
-You, sir, are a genius.
-It's a hobby.

553
00:29:32,000 --> 00:29:33,480
Mr President, answer the phone.

554
00:29:40,440 --> 00:29:41,600
Hello?

555
00:29:42,480 --> 00:29:44,000
This is President Nixon.

556
00:29:44,080 --> 00:29:46,280
GIRL: It's here!
The spaceman's here!

557
00:29:46,640 --> 00:29:49,200
It's going to get me!
It's going to eat me!

558
00:29:49,320 --> 00:29:50,800
There's no time for
a SWAT team, let's go.

559
00:29:50,880 --> 00:29:52,000
Mr President,
tell her help's on the way.

560
00:29:52,080 --> 00:29:53,680
Canton, on no account
follow me into this box

561
00:29:53,760 --> 00:29:56,960
-and close the door behind you.
-What the hell are you doing?

562
00:29:58,760 --> 00:29:59,760
(WHOOSHING)

563
00:30:02,120 --> 00:30:03,880
GIRL: Mr President! Please help.

564
00:30:04,360 --> 00:30:05,520
Please help me!

565
00:30:05,760 --> 00:30:07,600
Jefferson, it's all right.

566
00:30:08,280 --> 00:30:09,640
I'm sending my best people.

567
00:30:14,480 --> 00:30:16,840
DOCTOR: Jefferson isn't a girl's
name. It's not her name, either.

568
00:30:16,920 --> 00:30:18,680
Jefferson, Adams, Hamilton. River?

569
00:30:18,800 --> 00:30:20,680
Surnames of three of
America's founding fathers.

570
00:30:20,760 --> 00:30:22,680
Lovely fellows. Two of them fancied me.

571
00:30:23,800 --> 00:30:25,840
Are you okay, coping?

572
00:30:26,000 --> 00:30:28,040
You see, the President
asked the child two questions,

573
00:30:28,240 --> 00:30:29,480
"Where are you?" and "Who are you?"

574
00:30:29,560 --> 00:30:30,640
She was answering "where".

575
00:30:30,720 --> 00:30:32,760
It's bigger on the inside.

576
00:30:32,840 --> 00:30:34,000
Ah, you get used to it.

577
00:30:34,080 --> 00:30:35,120
DOCTOR: Now, where would you find

578
00:30:35,200 --> 00:30:36,920
three big historical names
in a row like that?

579
00:30:37,000 --> 00:30:38,200
-Where?
-Here.

580
00:30:39,440 --> 00:30:40,680
Come on!

581
00:30:43,480 --> 00:30:44,520
It's, uh...

582
00:30:44,600 --> 00:30:45,960
Are you taking care of this?

583
00:30:46,040 --> 00:30:47,840
Why is it always my turn?

584
00:30:48,520 --> 00:30:50,040
Because you're the newest.

585
00:30:53,000 --> 00:30:54,240
AMY: Where are we?

586
00:30:54,320 --> 00:30:56,720
About five miles
from Cape Kennedy Space Center.

587
00:30:56,800 --> 00:31:00,120
It's 1969, the year of the moon.

588
00:31:00,200 --> 00:31:01,480
Interesting, don't you think?

589
00:31:01,560 --> 00:31:03,080
But why would a little girl be here?

590
00:31:03,160 --> 00:31:04,640
I don't know. Lost me a bit.

591
00:31:04,720 --> 00:31:06,160
The President asked the girl
where she was

592
00:31:06,240 --> 00:31:08,440
and she did what any lost
little girl would do.

593
00:31:08,680 --> 00:31:10,440
She looked out of the window.

594
00:31:12,920 --> 00:31:15,760
Streets! Of course, street names.

595
00:31:15,840 --> 00:31:18,160
The only place in Florida,
probably all of America,

596
00:31:18,240 --> 00:31:20,080
with those three street names
on the same junction.

597
00:31:20,200 --> 00:31:22,320
And Dr Song,
you've got that face on again.

598
00:31:22,440 --> 00:31:23,480
What face?

599
00:31:23,560 --> 00:31:24,760
The "he's hot when he's clever" face.

600
00:31:24,840 --> 00:31:26,640
-This is my normal face.
-Yes, it is.

601
00:31:26,720 --> 00:31:28,680
-Oh, shut up.
-Not a chance.

602
00:31:32,240 --> 00:31:33,280
We've moved.

603
00:31:33,360 --> 00:31:35,960
How can we have moved?

604
00:31:36,040 --> 00:31:38,160
You haven't even got
to space travel yet?

605
00:31:38,480 --> 00:31:41,560
I was going to cover it
with time travel.

606
00:31:41,760 --> 00:31:44,280
-Time travel?
-Braveheart Canton, come on.

607
00:31:44,920 --> 00:31:47,040
So we're in a box
that's bigger on the inside

608
00:31:47,120 --> 00:31:48,960
-and it travels through time and space?
-Yeah, basically.

609
00:31:49,040 --> 00:31:50,600
How long have Scotland Yard had this?

610
00:31:52,000 --> 00:31:53,880
RIVER: It's a warehouse
of some kind, disused.

611
00:31:54,000 --> 00:31:56,480
DOCTOR: You realise this is
almost certainly a trap, of course?

612
00:31:56,600 --> 00:31:58,400
I noticed the phone, yes.

613
00:31:58,480 --> 00:32:00,160
AMY: What about it?
RIVER: It was cut off.

614
00:32:00,360 --> 00:32:02,400
So how did the child phone from here?

615
00:32:02,480 --> 00:32:04,440
AMY: Okay, but why would
anyone want to trap us?

616
00:32:04,680 --> 00:32:07,960
DOCTOR: Dunno. Let's see if anyone
tries to kill us and work backwards.

617
00:32:12,280 --> 00:32:13,840
(RHYTHMIC DEEP BREATHING)

618
00:32:15,240 --> 00:32:17,200
Now, why would a little girl be here?

619
00:32:17,440 --> 00:32:20,680
DOCTOR: I don't know.
Let's find her and ask her.

620
00:32:24,440 --> 00:32:26,520
RIVER: It's non terrestrial.
Definitely alien.

621
00:32:27,320 --> 00:32:29,200
Probably not even from this time zone.

622
00:32:29,840 --> 00:32:32,400
Which is odd, because look at this!

623
00:32:33,720 --> 00:32:35,480
It's earth tech, contemporary.

624
00:32:35,560 --> 00:32:38,400
Very contemporary, cutting-edge.
This is from the space programme!

625
00:32:38,480 --> 00:32:40,240
-RIVER: Stolen?
-What, by aliens?

626
00:32:40,680 --> 00:32:41,720
Apparently.

627
00:32:41,800 --> 00:32:43,960
But why? I mean, if you can
make it all the way to Earth,

628
00:32:44,040 --> 00:32:46,200
why steal technology that
can barely make it to the moon?

629
00:32:46,480 --> 00:32:49,720
Maybe 'cause it's cooler!
Look how cool this stuff is!

630
00:32:49,920 --> 00:32:51,000
Cool aliens?

631
00:32:51,080 --> 00:32:52,880
Well, what would you call me?

632
00:32:52,960 --> 00:32:54,360
-An alien.
-Oi!

633
00:32:54,440 --> 00:32:56,960
I, uh... I think he's okay now.

634
00:32:57,040 --> 00:32:58,800
DOCTOR: Ah! Back with us, Canton?

635
00:32:59,720 --> 00:33:01,680
-I like your wheels.
-That's my boy.

636
00:33:02,000 --> 00:33:04,480
So come on. Little girl, let's find her.

637
00:33:07,800 --> 00:33:09,560
-River...
-I know what you're thinking.

638
00:33:09,640 --> 00:33:10,880
No, you don't.

639
00:33:10,960 --> 00:33:14,000
You're thinking, "If we can find
the spaceman in 1969 and neutralise it,

640
00:33:14,080 --> 00:33:16,520
"then it won't be around
in 2011 to kill the Doctor."

641
00:33:17,280 --> 00:33:18,960
Okay, lucky guess.

642
00:33:19,640 --> 00:33:21,640
It's only because
I was thinking it, too.

643
00:33:22,200 --> 00:33:23,680
So let's do it.

644
00:33:23,760 --> 00:33:25,000
It doesn't work like that.

645
00:33:25,720 --> 00:33:27,840
We came here because of
what we saw in the future.

646
00:33:28,280 --> 00:33:31,320
If we try and prevent the future
from happening, we create a paradox.

647
00:33:31,480 --> 00:33:33,160
Time can be rewritten.

648
00:33:33,240 --> 00:33:34,920
-Not all of it.
-Says who?

649
00:33:35,000 --> 00:33:36,640
Who do you think?

650
00:33:36,760 --> 00:33:38,200
What's this?

651
00:33:38,440 --> 00:33:42,200
-We can still save him...
-Doctor, look at this.

652
00:33:47,000 --> 00:33:48,520
So where does that go?

653
00:33:50,400 --> 00:33:52,600
RIVER: There's a network of
tunnels running under here.

654
00:33:52,760 --> 00:33:55,680
-Life signs?
-No, nothing that's showing up.

655
00:33:55,760 --> 00:33:57,200
Those are the worst kind.

656
00:33:57,400 --> 00:33:58,640
Be careful!

657
00:33:58,720 --> 00:34:01,080
Careful? I tried that once.

658
00:34:01,520 --> 00:34:02,880
Ever so dull.

659
00:34:02,960 --> 00:34:07,160
-Shout if you get in trouble.
-Don't worry, I'm quite the screamer.

660
00:34:07,840 --> 00:34:09,560
Now, there's a spoiler for you.

661
00:34:09,720 --> 00:34:11,520
So what's going on here?

662
00:34:11,640 --> 00:34:13,560
Uh, nothing. She's just a friend.

663
00:34:15,480 --> 00:34:17,920
I think he's talking about
the possible alien incursion.

664
00:34:19,200 --> 00:34:20,480
Okay.

665
00:34:40,560 --> 00:34:42,480
(ALIENS CHITTERING)

666
00:34:52,680 --> 00:34:53,720
So,

667
00:34:55,960 --> 00:34:57,600
I was in a bar, having a drink.

668
00:34:58,160 --> 00:35:01,040
Tell me honestly, am I still there?

669
00:35:01,280 --> 00:35:02,640
Afraid not.

670
00:35:04,000 --> 00:35:05,520
(PANTING)

671
00:35:07,440 --> 00:35:08,760
All clear.

672
00:35:08,920 --> 00:35:10,280
Just tunnels.

673
00:35:10,360 --> 00:35:12,120
Nothing down there I can see.

674
00:35:12,720 --> 00:35:14,120
Uh, give me five minutes.

675
00:35:14,200 --> 00:35:15,720
I want to take another look around.

676
00:35:16,240 --> 00:35:17,760
Stupidly dangerous!

677
00:35:17,840 --> 00:35:20,040
Yep! I like it, too.

678
00:35:20,760 --> 00:35:23,360
Amy, look after him.

679
00:35:26,760 --> 00:35:28,520
Rory, would you mind going with her?

680
00:35:29,040 --> 00:35:30,200
Yeah, a bit.

681
00:35:30,280 --> 00:35:32,040
Then I appreciate it all the more.

682
00:35:35,040 --> 00:35:36,560
Hang on, River.

683
00:35:36,720 --> 00:35:37,760
I'm coming, too.

684
00:35:44,800 --> 00:35:46,000
You okay?

685
00:35:46,080 --> 00:35:47,480
Ah, yes, yes.

686
00:35:47,560 --> 00:35:48,920
I just felt a bit sick.

687
00:35:49,560 --> 00:35:51,360
It's the prison food, probably.

688
00:35:54,320 --> 00:35:57,640
Okay, this way?

689
00:35:57,720 --> 00:35:59,360
What do you think?

690
00:36:24,840 --> 00:36:26,120
I keep thinking I hear things.

691
00:36:26,280 --> 00:36:29,080
It's interesting. These tunnels are old.

692
00:36:29,640 --> 00:36:31,200
Really old.

693
00:36:31,600 --> 00:36:34,160
How can they be really old
and nobody notice them?

694
00:36:43,280 --> 00:36:44,600
It's a maintenance hatch.

695
00:36:44,840 --> 00:36:46,280
It's locked.

696
00:36:46,600 --> 00:36:48,400
Oh, why do people always lock things?

697
00:36:48,480 --> 00:36:49,640
What's through there?

698
00:36:49,720 --> 00:36:51,880
-RIVER: I've no idea.
-Something bad?

699
00:36:52,040 --> 00:36:53,200
Almost definitely.

700
00:36:53,360 --> 00:36:55,360
You're going to open it, aren't you?

701
00:36:55,560 --> 00:36:56,960
Well, it's locked.

702
00:36:57,080 --> 00:36:58,480
How's a girl supposed to resist?

703
00:36:59,000 --> 00:37:02,080
-Is this sensible?
-God, I hope not.

704
00:37:05,080 --> 00:37:07,720
Yeah, you and the Doctor,
I can kind of picture it.

705
00:37:08,360 --> 00:37:09,960
Keep a look out.

706
00:37:13,400 --> 00:37:15,080
What did you mean?

707
00:37:15,800 --> 00:37:17,600
What you said to Amy,

708
00:37:18,200 --> 00:37:19,920
there's a worse day coming for you?

709
00:37:24,040 --> 00:37:25,640
When I first met the Doctor,

710
00:37:26,520 --> 00:37:28,360
a long, long time ago,

711
00:37:30,160 --> 00:37:31,440
he knew all about me.

712
00:37:33,960 --> 00:37:35,600
Think about that.

713
00:37:37,080 --> 00:37:39,160
Impressionable young girl and suddenly,

714
00:37:39,240 --> 00:37:41,920
this man just drops out of the sky.

715
00:37:42,240 --> 00:37:45,120
And he's clever and mad and wonderful

716
00:37:45,800 --> 00:37:47,720
and knows every last thing about her.

717
00:37:49,400 --> 00:37:51,240
Imagine what that does to a girl.

718
00:37:52,280 --> 00:37:53,760
I don't really have to.

719
00:37:54,880 --> 00:37:56,400
Trouble is it's all back-to-front.

720
00:37:57,560 --> 00:37:59,680
My past is his future.

721
00:38:00,760 --> 00:38:02,280
We're travelling in opposite directions.

722
00:38:03,840 --> 00:38:06,200
Every time we meet, I know him more,

723
00:38:07,240 --> 00:38:08,880
he knows me less.

724
00:38:11,560 --> 00:38:13,280
I live for the days when I see him,

725
00:38:17,360 --> 00:38:18,960
but I know that every time I do,

726
00:38:19,880 --> 00:38:21,520
he'll be one step further away.

727
00:38:24,040 --> 00:38:25,480
And the day is coming

728
00:38:25,600 --> 00:38:27,560
when I'll look into that man's eyes,

729
00:38:30,280 --> 00:38:31,640
my Doctor,

730
00:38:35,560 --> 00:38:37,680
and he won't have
the faintest idea who I am.

731
00:38:39,400 --> 00:38:40,920
(WHIRRS)

732
00:38:47,320 --> 00:38:48,880
And I think it's going to kill me.

733
00:39:13,280 --> 00:39:15,240
What is this place?

734
00:39:17,680 --> 00:39:20,520
That's an alarm.
Check if anything's coming.

735
00:39:24,600 --> 00:39:26,280
(CHITTERING)

736
00:39:32,440 --> 00:39:34,120
There's nothing out there.

737
00:39:45,960 --> 00:39:49,000
These tunnels, they're not just here,
they're everywhere.

738
00:39:50,520 --> 00:39:53,280
They're running under the surface
of the entire planet.

739
00:39:54,600 --> 00:39:56,240
They've been here for centuries.

740
00:40:03,200 --> 00:40:04,320
Rory!

741
00:40:06,000 --> 00:40:07,040
So,

742
00:40:07,800 --> 00:40:11,040
you were kicked out of the FBI
because you had attitude problems?

743
00:40:11,600 --> 00:40:14,080
No, I just wanted to get married.

744
00:40:14,800 --> 00:40:17,560
-Is that a crime?
-Yes.

745
00:40:19,200 --> 00:40:21,480
Doctor who, exactly?

746
00:40:21,920 --> 00:40:22,960
Ah...

747
00:40:24,000 --> 00:40:25,360
That's classified.

748
00:40:25,440 --> 00:40:28,000
-Classified by whom?
-God knows.

749
00:40:28,240 --> 00:40:29,920
Do you work for him?

750
00:40:30,000 --> 00:40:33,520
He's my friend,
if friend is the right word.

751
00:40:34,720 --> 00:40:36,400
I haven't seen him in a while.

752
00:40:39,320 --> 00:40:44,040
I had something I wanted to tell him,
but stuff always gets in the way.

753
00:40:45,440 --> 00:40:46,880
Stuff does that.

754
00:40:46,960 --> 00:40:48,520
GIRL: Help me!

755
00:40:51,560 --> 00:40:54,200
-Help! Help me!
-That's her.

756
00:40:55,840 --> 00:40:57,520
-(GROANING)
-Amy?

757
00:40:57,600 --> 00:40:59,200
-GIRL: Help me, please!
-What's wrong?

758
00:40:59,280 --> 00:41:00,840
I need to tell you something.
It's important.

759
00:41:00,920 --> 00:41:02,200
-Doctor!
-It's really, really important.

760
00:41:02,280 --> 00:41:04,360
-Doctor, quickly!
-What, now?

761
00:41:11,280 --> 00:41:14,040
Canton! Canton! Are you okay?

762
00:41:14,200 --> 00:41:16,000
Is he all right?

763
00:41:16,280 --> 00:41:18,320
Just unconscious. Got a proper whack.

764
00:41:18,440 --> 00:41:20,480
Doctor, I need to tell you something.

765
00:41:20,560 --> 00:41:22,160
-I have to tell you it now.
-Not a great moment.

766
00:41:22,240 --> 00:41:24,720
No, it's important. It has to be now.

767
00:41:24,800 --> 00:41:26,840
GIRL: Help! Help me!

768
00:41:31,040 --> 00:41:33,280
-Help me!
-Doctor,

769
00:41:35,320 --> 00:41:36,760
I'm pregnant.

770
00:41:39,520 --> 00:41:41,480
(RHYTHMIC THUDDING)

771
00:41:51,600 --> 00:41:54,080
That's it, the astronaut.

772
00:42:09,680 --> 00:42:12,400
-Help me!
-Get down!

773
00:42:12,840 --> 00:42:15,640
-What are you doing?
-Saving your life!

774
00:42:15,720 --> 00:42:17,720
-No!
-(GUN FIRING)

775
00:42:17,800 --> 00:42:19,320
(SCREAMING)

776
00:42:53,640 --> 00:42:55,480
I'm sorry. I didn't mean to shoot you.

777
00:42:56,040 --> 00:42:57,840
MISSION CONTROL:
Thirty seconds and counting.

778
00:42:57,920 --> 00:43:00,160
We are still go with Apollo 11.

779
00:43:00,640 --> 00:43:01,920
DOCTOR: They are everywhere.

780
00:43:02,000 --> 00:43:04,280
RORY: It's like they edit themselves
out of your memory

781
00:43:04,520 --> 00:43:06,880
-as soon as you look away.
- Twenty seconds and counting.

782
00:43:06,960 --> 00:43:08,640
AMY: We still don't know
what they look like.

783
00:43:08,800 --> 00:43:11,200
DOCTOR: As long as there's been
something in the corner of your eye

784
00:43:11,280 --> 00:43:13,560
or creaking in your house
or breathing under your bed

785
00:43:13,640 --> 00:43:14,880
or voices through a wall.

786
00:43:14,960 --> 00:43:15,960
MISSION CONTROL: 7 minus 10...

787
00:43:16,120 --> 00:43:18,640
DOCTOR: We are not fighting an
alien invasion.

788
